<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Weather Satellite Launched From Plesetsk 25 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501070694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0653 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501070694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Semen Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 25 TASS -- Russia successfully 
launched the "Meteor-3" meteorological satellite early on 
Tuesday after the blast off was postponed for three times. 
  The satellite carries the German "Tubsat" minisatellite and 
is fitted out with the German "Prare" system and the 
Russian-French "Skarab" equipment. 
  The satellite which blasted off from the Russian Plesetsk 
cosmodrome onboard the "Tsiklon" booster is intended for 
round-the-clock processing and transmission of 
hydrometeorological information, as well as of data on 
radioactivitity in near-earth space and the state of 
magnetosphere and the ozone layer, TASS was told at the press 
service of the Russian aerospace forces. 

</TEXT>

