<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finnish Prime Minister Favors Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2701124394 Tallinn BNS in English 1054 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2701124394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 27, BNS -- Finnish Prime Minister Esko 
Aho, speaking at a Parliamentary Assembly meeting of the Council 
of Europe [CE] in Strasbourg Tuesday [25 January], expressed 
support to an early membership of Russia in the European body, 
the head of the Estonian delegation said in a telephone 
interview with BNS. 
  "It needs to be emphasized that the Russians have chosen 
democracy," Aho said. He said becoming a member in the Council 
of Europe was an important step in the process of 
democratization. Therefore, Russia and the other countries that 
have expressed the wish to join the CE should be accepted as 
quickly as possible, the Finnish leader said. 
  When asked by the head of the Estonian delegation to the 
meeting, Tunne Kelam, if Russia should become a CE member even 
before it has withdrawn its troops from Estonia and Latvia, Aho 
said he favored the pullout of Russian troops, but added that 
Russia had to be accepted into the European body in any case. 
  Finland on Wednesday was the only country in the Strasbourg 
meeting to give its unconditional support to granting Russia a 
full member status. Russian officials have already made a 
number of statements hailing Finland. 

</TEXT>

