<H3> <TI>   Central, East European States Discuss Security Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601193694 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 1506 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2601193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev, 26 Jan -- The foreign ministries of central 
and eastern European countries are holding multilateral working 
consultations on issues of regional security in Ukraine for the 
first time ever. They are discussing general issues of security 
in central and eastern Europe, in particular, Ukraine's 
initiative on setting up a zone of stable security in the region. 
  During a conversation with a UNIAR correspondent, Ihor 
Kharchenko, chief of the Ukrainian Foreign Ministry's department 
of political analysis and planning, underscored that 
participants in the consultations support the signing of the 
trilateral declaration in Moscow and expressed hope that such 
consultations will be held in the future. It is worth 
mentioning that representatives of all the countries of eastern 
Europe are taking part in the consultations. The Czech Republic 
is taking part as an observer. 
  Ukrainian Deputy Foreign Minister Borys Tarasyuk and Dmytro 
Pavlychko, chairman of the [Ukrainian parliament] foreign 
affairs commission, addressed participants in the working 
consultations and explained Ukraine's stand on issues of 
consolidating security in central and eastern Europe. 

</TEXT>

