<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Baltic-Black Sea Alliance' Would Exclude Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2601114994 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 25 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2601114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Valeriy Gromak report: "Baltic-Black Sea Alliance </F>
Outlined. A Place Will Be Found in the Bloc for Many, But Not 
for Russia"] 
  [Text] Vilnius -- "NATO cannot now accept states which are 
not in complete accord," the well-known Ukrainian writer Dmitro 
Pavlychko, chairman of the Ukrainian parliament's Commission for 
Foreign Affairs, has stated. "Hence, in my view, we should 
first undergo schooling in accord all together, not separately. 
We must create complete harmony in East and Central Europe." 
  Dmitro Pavlychko made this statement during his tour of 
Baltic countries, where he held talks with the heads of the 
Lithuanian and Latvian parliaments and leaders of committees and 
commissions, ministers, and opposition leaders in those 
countries. His tour, the mass media reported, had one aim: the 
creation of a Baltic-Black Sea alliance or, to be more precise, 
joint work on the juridical basis for such an alliance. 
Lithuania and the other Baltic countries, Pavlychko believes, 
need to look south and break out of the circle to which they 
have been assigned. 
  So an effort is clearly being made to create a Baltic-Black 
Sea alliance. What role in this is allotted to Russia -- a 
state which has outlets to the Baltic and the Black Sea? 
Ukrainian parliamentarians expressed no opinion on this 
question. But it was answered back in December at the "Baltic 
Cooperation and Security" conference by former Estonian Defense 
Minister Juri Luik (now foreign minister). Expressing his 
support for the creation of a unified security concept for the 
Baltic countries, Luik called for the formation of a 
military-political alliance of the Baltic states without the 
participation of Russia, but involving Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

