<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Addresses Correspondents on Arrival in Beijing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601161994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1339 
GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2601161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Grigoriy Arslanov, </F>
Vyacheslav Tomilin, and Georgiy Shmelev] 
  [Excerpt] Beijing, 26 Jan -- Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev arrived in China on Wednesday [26 January], 
starting an official visit that will focus on Russian-Chinese 
border trade. Kozyrev, whose visit will last until 29 January, 
is to meet with Foreign Minister Qian Qichen in Beijing on 
Thursday. 
  Moscow regards mutual relations with the PRC as a 
traditionally high-priority and independent direction of its 
foreign policy and as an important component part of its general 
strategy of ensuring national-state interests through 
partnership with the surrounding world. To a great extent we 
link cooperation with China with the prospects of fulfilling the 
unique Euro-Asiatic potential of Russia, the economic upsurge of 
the rayons of Siberia and the Far East and integration into the 
economic life of the Asia-Pacific region. 
  The Russian side values highly the results achieved in 
recent 
years of cooperation with China that has been carried out on 
many levels and is satisfied with the stable and positive 
development along all paths of bilateral links. The bringing of 
Russian-Chinese relations on to a higher level -- that of 
constructive partners -- accords completely with the national 
interests of our countries and peoples, the head of the Russian 
Federation's foreign policy department told ITAR-TASS 
correspondents at Beijing airport. 
  The coming talks and meetings in Beijing are expected to be 
a 
new step forward on the path of strengthening 
good-neighborliness and deepening mutual understanding and trust 
between Russia and the PRC, while the documents signed during 
the visit will expand the treaty and legal base of bilateral 
relations. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

