<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Round of Talks Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701101994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0842 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701101994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Grigoriy Arslanov, </F>
Vyacheslav Tomilin, and Georgiy Shmelev] 
  [Text] Beijing January 27 TASS -- Questions of bilateral 
relations were in the focus of the first round of talks between 
the foreign ministers of Russia and China, which has just ended 
here. "Its agenda was so crammed that the foreign ministers of 
the two countries had to prolong the talk for almost one hour," 
said Galina Sidorova, political adviser of the Russian foreign 
minister. 
  The ministers stressed that "a progressive and constant 
exchange of views and visits at summit and high levels would be 
continued between the two countries. A visit of PRC chairman 
Jiang Zemin to Moscow is being planned. It will apparently take 
place in the third quarter of the year. In preparation for a 
new Russo-Chinese summit, Russian Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin 
will visit Beijing and Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen will 
pay a visit to Moscow. 
  In the course of the negotiations, Sidorova noted, the sides 
have discussed various aspects of economic and 
military-technical cooperation between the two countries. 
Kozyrev stressed Russia's readiness to go over to large-scale 
ventures while simultaneously continuing the policy of expanding 
traditional forms of economic relations. For instance, Russia 
is expected to take part in the construction of the huge "three 
gorges" hydropower complex in China. 
  The sides also discussed the possibility of Russia helping 
China to reconstruct many enterprises, which were built with 
Soviet aid. 
  The ministers noted the progress made during the talks on 
the 
mutual reduction of armed forces and confidence-building 
measures on the border between the two countries. These talks 
will be continued to try to conclude a corresponding agreement 
already this year, Sidorova said. 
  The sides announced their readiness to continue negotiations 
on border problems. The joint delegation of Russia, Kazakhstan, 
Tajikistan and Kyrgyzstan to these talks will be led by 
Aleksandr Panov, the new Russian deputy foreign minister. 
  During the discussion of problems linked with the 
demarcation 
of the border between the two countries, the ministers pointed 
to the possibility of joint economic activity in the border 
districts, including the disputed areas. The sides want a 
status quo to be observed on the border after its demarcation. 
  Mutual interest in developing constructive cooperation in 
the 
military-technical sphere was expressed in the course of the 
talks. Kozyrev said that it should be promoted with due account 
of mutual interests and the observance of corresponding 
international commitments. 
  Sidorova noted that the idea of promoting constructive 
partnership with China, expressed by the Russian minister, "Does 
not mean that we are allies with China in the direct sense of 
the term. It implies Moscow's readiness to promote very close 
interaction with Beijing in matters of mutual concern". 
Moreover, Russia and China, as two great powers, proceed from 
the understanding that they have both national and huge common 
interests of regional and global character. 
  In reply to a request of his Chinese counterpart, Kozyrev 
shared his view with him on the current political situation in 
Russia, laying stress on the immutability of its foreign policy 
which "remains presidential". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

