<H3> <TI>   Details on Yeltsin's 3 Feb Visit to Tbilisi Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701121194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1057 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701121194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Boris Yeltsin will stay one day, February 3, in 
Tbilisi, informed sources in that city told Interfax. The 
visit is said to have been originally scheduled for February 3 
or 4 and have a one day program. 
  This includes a tete-a-tete with the Georgian leader Eduard 
Shevardnadze, negotiations between the delegations, a meeting of 
the Russian president with Georgian intellectuals and an 
official ceremony of signing Russo-Georgian documents, notably 
the Friendship and Cooperation Treaty. 
  Final touches are said to be put on about 20 bilateral 
documents. Only those that are finalized will be signed. 
  Colonel Gennadiy Dolgachyov, head of the Russian Army Group 
in Transcaucasia press office, told Interfax that President 
Yeltsin would be accompanied by Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev who would sign with Georgian military officials a treaty 
on the status of Russian troops in Georgia and numerous other 
documents on military cooperation between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

