<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgian Defense Minister Visits Missile Base </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601195494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2217 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2601195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 26 TASS -- Belgian Defence Minister 
Leo Delcroix has become the first NATO official to visit a 
once-secret Russian missile base in Bologoye located between 
Moscow and St. Petersburg. 
  Accompanied by his Russian counterpart Pavel Grachev, 
Delcroix toured the base, once off-limits for foreigners, to see 
the most advanced Russian strategic missiles and other military 
hardware. 
  The trip was part of Delcroix's two-day visit to Russia, 
following the signing of a cooperation agreement by president 
Boris Yeltsin and Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene in 
Brussels in December 1993 to boost military contacts between the 
two countries. 
  Delcroix's talks with Grachev centered around international 
security in the wake of the adoption of the Partnership for 
Peace programme proposed by U.S. President Bill Clinton and the 
historic U.S.-Russian-Ukrainian nuclear deal signed in Moscow 
earlier this month. 
  Special attention was paid to European security, nuclear 
non- 
proliferation and the participation of both countries in U.N. 
peace-keeping operations in Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

