<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko: Reshuffle Strengthens Yeltsin's Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601164094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1354 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2601164094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vladimir Shumeyko, the Chairman of the Federation 
Council, the upper house of the Russian parliament, said the 
election of the new legislature and the reorganization of the 
government had strengthened the president's positions. 
  He said to reporters on Wednesday that Yegor Gaydar's 
resignation as first deputy premier had not ended his political 
career. "We'll see him working in the Russian government some 
time in the future," Shumeyko said. 
  He rejected the suggestion that Gaydar's resignation meant 
an 
end to the economic reforms. "Only Gaydar, Fedorov and Shumeyko 
have left the government," the rest of its members remaining in 
office, Shumeyko said. 
  He said the recent reorganization had made the government 
more compact and potentially more efficient. "I hope this 
government stays in office until the new presidential election, 
prior to which it has to resign under the Constitution," he 
said. 
  He did not rule out that the Russia's Choice bloc, headed by 
Gaydar, would come to be in opposition to the Chernomyrdin 
government. But this would only be clear after the government 
approved proposed amendments to its economic policy, he said. 
  Shumeyko said the resignation of Gaydar and Fedorov would 
not 
affect Russia's relations with its Western partners. But Russia 
is "a powerful sovereign state, which will not allow anyone to 
lecture it," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

