<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yazov Denies Involvement in Deaths </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601163994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1354 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2601163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Former Soviet Defense Minister Dmitriy Yazov has 
denied accusations of his involvement in the death of three 
persons during the August 1991 putsch. At the court hearings in 
Moscow Wednesday he said that soldiers had to shoot only under 
extreme conditions. He said that in line with the military 
regulations servicemen have the right to use fire arms in case 
of an attack on a patrol. 
  Yazov said that the eight armored personnel carriers that 
moved along the Garden Ring were patrol vehicles and soldiers 
inside them were forced to open fire when they faced danger to 
their lives. 
  The ex-minister said that as a result of the investigation 
into the murder of three persons, experts found no corpus 
delicti in the actions of servicemen of the Taman Division who 
were involved in the incident. 
  The court hearings will continue January 27 at 10 a.m. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

