<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supreme Council Approves Privatization Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601183994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1704 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2601183994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] By a majority of 245 votes out of 440, the Ukrainian 
Supreme Soviet today approved the draft resolution "On the state 
program for privatization in 1994." Only 34 votes were cast 
against the program. 
  According to the program, a total of 20,000 small 
businesses, 
1,400 unfinished construction projects and 8,000 medium and 
major industries will be privatized in 1994. 
  As a result, Ukraine's private sector will amount to 
28% of 
the country's economy. The state will receive over 21 Tn 
[Trillion] karbovantsy and over $230 Mn. 
  The properties of state bodies, National Space Agency, TV 
and 
radio broadcasting centers, publishers' and port facilities are 
not subject to privatization. 
  The chairman of the state privatization fund, Vladimir 
Pryadko, did not rule out that the adoption of the privatization 
program on the eve of the future parliamentary elections 
scheduled for March 27 was a measure of political character. In 
his opinion, "the Supreme Soviet's conservative nature hampered 
the process of privatization in the republic." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

