<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fired Crimean Official Not To Leave Political Arena </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701110094 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 25 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2701110094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "I. Yermakov's News Conference"] </F>
  [Text] Ivan Yermakov, dismissed from his post of Ukrainian 
presidential representative in Sevastopol, stated at the news 
conference that he was not going to leave the political arena 
and that, in his opinion, "Leonid Kravchuk did not do the right 
thing" when he signed the edict on his dismissal. "This should 
not have been done with such a difficult situation prevailing in 
the Crimea," said Yermakov. He pointed out that he will not run 
for the Ukrainian Supreme Council, but will be a candidate for 
deputy of the Crimean Supreme Council. He also promised that he 
would return to his post, no matter what it is called (his dream 
is to become mayor of Sevastopol). Yermakov stated that he was 
going to create a Slavic Christian Party that will also be open 
to Muslims, Judaists, and all other people irrespective of their 
nationality. He focused on the fact that, over the period of 
his work as Ukrainian presidential representative in Sevastopol, 
he had to go through quite a number of unpleasant moments and 
even hours. In particular, it was when he had to hoist the 
Ukrainian state flag at the building of the city state 
administration, since "the colors of that flag do not appeal to 
me." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

