<H3> <TI>   Customs Head Views Cooperation Pact With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2601183494 Minsk DOBRY VECHAR in Belarusian 20 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> WS2601183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk DOBRY VECHAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Belarusian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by BELINFORM correspondent Alyaksandr Lyushkevich </F>
under the "Facts and Comments" rubric: "Our Customs Will 
Cooperate"] 
  [Text] During Bill Clinton's visit to Minsk, the Government 
of the United States and the Republic of Belarus signed an 
agreement on cooperation and mutual assistance between their 
respective customs services. A BELINFORM correspondent has 
asked Hyenadz Shkurdz, chairman of the State Committee for 
Customs, to comment on this agreement. 
  "This is the first governmental agreement on cooperation of 
our customs service with one of its foreign counterparts. It 
will become effective 90 days after the date of signing. 
  "This document provides that the two sides will assist one 
another in preventing and investigating any violations of the 
law, which are within the competence of their customs services. 
According to the agreement, the sides will provide each other 
with all information concerning the imposition of custom duties 
and other taxes. It is also very important that the sides 
assist each other in providing customs services with modern 
equipment. This also includes personnel training and the 
exchange of information on the latest developments in 'customs' 
equipment. That is of the greatest importance for us right now. 
The agreement also provides for the exchange of experts." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

