<DATE1>  27 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   South Ossetian Leaders on Russo-Georgian Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701121394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1057 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A comprehensive Russo-Georgian treaty to be signed 
in Tbilisi in early February will make the situation in the 
Caucasus, as well as in South Ossetia, worse still, South 
Ossetian Prime Minister Rezo Khugayev told Interfax. 
  He recalled that Moscow had not agreed to sign such a treaty 
before Georgia resolved its differences with South Ossetia and 
Abkhazia by political means. Georgia, however, has not even 
started an equal political dialog with those republics, Khugayev 
thinks. 
  He believes that Russian support for an indivisible Georgia 
"will give a free hand to chauvinist forces in Tbilisi." He did 
not rule out the possibility that, once the treaty was signed, 
Georgia would resume military pressure on South Ossetia and 
Abkhazia. 
  Lyudvig Chibirov, head of the South Ossetian parliament who 
also attended the interview, made it clear that the people of 
the republic would hardly agree even to a confederation within 
Georgia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

