<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Trip to France Viewed as `Positive' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2601150594 Yerevan SNARK in English 0755 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2601150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan SNARK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Georgia the visit of Eduard Shevardnadze to 
France is estimated to be positive in the whole. Commenting the 
results of the Paris negotiations, Giso Gilieshvli, the chairman 
of the Committee for External Economic Relations, told the 
agreement on the investments protection is ready for signing. 
French capital will be invested in the extension of the Poti 
port. Besides, French specialists will take part in the 
Tbilisi-Baku railway reconstruction to create a safe 
Europe-Caucasus-Asia way. It is also supposed to create a joint 
French-Georgian Bank. Irakli Shenghelia, the leader of the 
Georgian Christian-Democratic Union, said France is the 
initiator of the European integration idea, and Georgia has to 
join this process. Besides, there was a necessity to examine 
the reaction on the Georgia's entrance in CIS. In all 
probability, E. Shevardnadze tried to clear up in Paris the 
attitude of France to the coming discussion of the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict in the UN Security Council. On his 
return to Tbilisi the Georgian leader declared on a 
press-conference there was understanding of the necessity of the 
Georgia's entrance to CIS. "It was a right decision which should 
be acceptable for Georgia as well as for Europe and CIS", - said 
Shevardnadze. The agreement for Friendship, Cooperation and 
Mutual Aid was signed during the visit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

