<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Ambassador Meets Vice President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601170294 Almaty KAZTAG in Russian 1100 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2601170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty KAZTAG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vice President Yerik Asanbayev on 25 January 
received Korean Ambassador to Kazakhstan Kim Chang-kon at the 
latter's request. During the conversation they dealt with 
prospects for developing economic and cultural cooperation 
between our countries. 
  Bilateral official relations at present, noted Yerik 
Asanbayev, are exemplary and effective. South Korean 
businessmen in a short period of time have initiated production 
of televisions in Almaty and refrigerators in Karaganda. 
However, the dynamism of cooperation must be raised, especially 
in the sphere of providing credits to Kazakhstan. 
  To support the recently introduced national currency and to 
ease the transfer to a market economy we need support from 
outside, stressed the vice president. The republic needs to 
gather a critical mass of credits for a structural 
transformation of the economy and introduction of new technology 
in development of minerals. He expressed the confidence that 
the South Korean side, which at one time promised to allocate 
$350 million to Kazakhstan, will keep its word. Housing is 
built quickly and well in that country. To carry out the 
program of housing construction in our republic it is intended 
to make a close study of that experience in order to use it in 
action. Gratitude was expressed to the ambassador for 
humanitarian assistance to the value of 150,000 dollars, which 
had arrived that day in Almaty from Seoul. 
  Kim Chang-kon stated that he would exert every effort to 
strengthen friendly ties between the two countries, to improve 
economic links, and to attract businessmen from the Republic of 
Korea to Kazakhstan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

