<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Police Delay Turnover of Paldiski Office </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2701094994 Tallinn BNS in English 1927 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2701094994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 26, BNS -- The passport office of a 
Russian police station in the former military base town of 
Paldiski in Estonia has still not turned over to Estonian 
authorities the files of the town's registry of residents. 
Russian officials earlier had promised to end the delay and 
hand the files over by Jan. 27. 
  The head of the Russian passport office at Paldiski today 
failed to turn out for a scheduled meeting with the Estonian 
commandant of the town, Col. Raul Luks, said Taimi Laar, 
municipal secretary at Paldiski. 
  Estonian officials say it is impossible to prepare for 
elections for the Paldiski town council or establish a normal 
civilian rule in the town until the files are delivered. 
  Justice Minister Kaido Kama, however, has said the files 
drawn up and held by the local Russian police office without any 
authorized supervision lately cannot be trusted. He said that 
even if the files were to be returned, Estonia would still have 
to call a new municipal census, and the country's own officials 
will have to register the town's legal residents anew. 
  Laar said the Russian passport office until very lately had 
continued issuing Estonian resident's passport inscriptions, 
which currently is the only means of confirming the passport 
holder's permanent resident's status. 
  She insisted that the office close its doors finally by 
Thursday. "If they won't close the doors by Jan. 27, we will 
have every reason to raise alarm," she added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

