<H3> <TI>   Duma Chairman Receives U.S. Ambassador </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601175994 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1700 GMT 
26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2601175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ivan Rybkin, chairman of the State Duma, today 
received U.S. Ambassador to Russia Thomas Pickering, at the 
latter's request. According to the Federal Assembly's press 
service, the lengthy conversation touched on a broad circle of 
questions including the organization of the work of the State 
Duma and the priorities for its legislative work. 
  Rybkin noted that the plan for the work of the Duma has been 
coordinated with the activities of the president, the 
government, and other structures of power. The U.S. ambassador 
said that the United States was interested in the effective work 
of the Duma and was convinced of its necessity for Russia. In 
his opinion, its work will make it possible to resolve Russia's 
economic problems more quickly, including with the aid of the 
world community. 
  Pickering also proposed, on instructions from the U.S. 
Congress, assistance in organizing information technologies for 
the Russian Federal Assembly, ITAR-TASS reports. 

</TEXT>

