<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Second Unit Switched Off </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701120794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1057 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On Wednesday night [26 January], the second unit of 
Lithuania's Ignalina nuclear power plant was shut down. 
  This nuclear power plant's information department told 
Interfax that after the first unit was switched off on January 
18 following a water leek, the second unit worked at a capacity 
of 1300 megawatts. 
  The same source announced that the second unit had been shut 
down following the failure of the manual control system for the 
reactor's stages (a button on the control board went out of 
operation). 
  The administration of the nuclear power plant stated that 
despite those malfunctions, the system of automatic control and 
the safety equipment remained in a working condition. 
  The reactor was shut down according to the safety 
regulations. The radiation situation did not change, says the 
administration's official press release. 
  Repair work has been done already and preparations are 
underway for putting the reactor back into operation, presumably 
on Friday. 
  In view of the 2nd unit's stoppage, Lithuania experienced a 
shortage of energy on Thursday, Lithuania's Deputy Minister for 
Energy Saulius Kutas told Interfax. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

