<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belarusian Officials Deem Handover Illegal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601231694 Vilnius Radio Vilnius in English 2200 GMT 26 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2601231694 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In his interview with Lithuanian national radio 
Prime Minister Adolfas Slezevicius stated that relations between 
Lithuania and Belarus may deteriorate after two pro-Moscow 
communist leaders, who were among the organizers of the 1991 
January crackdown in Vilnius, had been brought back from Minsk 
to Vilnius by the Lithuanian law enforcement officers. 
  The Belarusian MPs [word indistinct] their top law and order 
officials of handing over Mykolas Burokevicius and Juozas 
Jermalavicius to the Lithuanian side on an illegal basis. On 
Tuesday the Belarusian Parliament accepted the resignation of 
the Interior Minister and [words indistinct] service chief. 
  According to Prime Minister Slezevicius, the detention of 
the 
two communist hardliners was carried out successfully and had 
been coordinated with the law enforcement institutions in 
Belarus.. 
  Meanwhile chairman of the Belarusian Parliamentary Committee 
on National Security, Mechislav Gryb, claims that the two men 
were detained in violation of the Belarusian and international 
law. 
  Speaking at a news conference in Minsk on Tuesday Mr. Gryb 
stated that the cases nine other persons wanted by the 
Lithuanian law enforcement authorities would be reviewed on a 
separate basis and that any kind of, as he called, illegal 
handover, like that of Burokevicius and Jermalavicius, would not 
happen in the future. 

</TEXT>

