<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Agreement Reached With Kaliningrad on Transit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601173394 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
1400 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2601173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Lithuanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baltic News Service has reported that Lithuanian and 
Kaliningrad negotiators failed to achieve any specific agreement 
on the transit of Russian passengers and cargo through the 
territory of Lithuania. 
  Yuriy Khlebnikov, an official from the international 
department at the Kaliningrad region administration office, told 
journalists at a news conference today that the talks failed to 
bring results. 
  The talks were headed by Virgilijus Bulovas, head of the 
group for the talks with the CIS and ambassador at large, and 
Harry Shmykhov, first deputy head of the Kaliningrad region. 
  A joint protocol has been prepared by the group experts from 
both sides, which confirms Lithuania's intention to open a 
Russian transit corridor on her territory. Although no dates 
have been mentioned, it is expected however that the corridor 
could start functioning at the end of the current year. Places 
in Lithuania will have to be earmarked and the procedure on how 
this transit will be controlled will have to be defined. 
  Lithuania is going to get acquainted with the experience of 
the West Berlin transit corridor, which was in operation until 
the Berlin Wall had been demolished. 
  It was announced that Lithuania proposed to simplify the 
procedure of granting transit visas at the border crossing 
points to cargo vehicles carrying so-called national economy 
goods. It was announced at the news conference in Kaliningrad 
that all the Russian passenger trains except two would travel 
through Lithuania non-stop and without border checks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

