<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition on LSDP Attempt To Oust Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2601143794 Tallinn BNS in English 1139 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2601143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 26, BNS -- MP Andrius Kubilius, member 
of the parliament's rightist opposition, said it would hard to 
support an intiative of the Lithuanian Social Democratic Party 
[LSDP] to take a no confidence vote in the Lithuanian government. 
  Kubilius said the LSDP statement, urging other political 
forces to back their initiative, lacks forecasts. "It is not 
hard to collect 28 votes that are necessary to start the no 
confidence process, but 71 votes are needed to express no 
confidence." This means that the no confidence vote would have 
to be supported by some members of the ruling majority, the 
lawmaker said. 
  Kubilius did not deny reports, however, that several members 
of the ruling Lithuanian Democratic Labor Party would back to 
move in secret voting. In his opinion, the rightist opposition, 
the social democrats and those several members of the LDLP may 
become "a new parliamentary majority, which will be able to form 
a new government." 
  The lawmaker said the social democrats do not forecast 
possible steps of the president -- will he make the government 
resign or will he dissolve the parliament. 
  Kubilius said he has serious doubts about the indicated 
motives of the initiative. "I think that the accusations against 
the present government should be much more serious than 
non-fulfillment of the LSDP's instructions." 

</TEXT>

