<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian `Source' on Armenian Troop Request </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2601151094 Baku TURAN in English 1810 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2601151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Baku TURAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baku (January 25) TURAN--Armenia asked Russia to 
help in solving the problems regarding displacement of Russian 
troops at the borders of Azerbaijan with Iran. This problem was 
briefly discussed during the talks between Russian and Armenian 
Ministers of Foreign Affairs Andrey Kozyrev and Vahan Papazyan 
on January 20 in Moscow, a reliable source from Russian Ministry 
of Foreign Affairs reported. 
  Yerevan believes, that "being cut off from Iran by a Russian 
buffer, Azerbaijan will be more complacent at the negotiation 
table, and at the fronts as well". 
  The same source informed, that "the Russian party has the 
impression, Armenian side is looking for a respite after the 
serious defeats it was incurred during the recent battles." 
  According to the plan, Azerbaijan is to give broad political 
autonomy to mountainous Karabakh, "to offer as a gift", Shusha 
to the Armenians and to work out a plan for "humanitarian 
corridors" from Armenia to mountainous Karabakh via the towns of 
Lachin and Kelbadzhar. 
  This plan of Andranik Mihranyan, Russian president's adviser 
also envisions the creation of a demilitarized buffer zone, 
along all the borders of mountainous Karabakh. The 
responsibility for administrative-legal control in the zone will 
be carried out by the Russian peacemaking forces. 
  Representative of so-called RMK [Republic of Mountainous 
Karabakh] Arkadiy Gukasyan, as a member of delegation from the 
Republic of Armenia was participating in negotiations with 
Kozyrev. However, according to the official report of Russian 
Minister of Foreign Affairs Andrey Kozyrev met Papazyan and 
Gukasyan separately. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

