<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Continues Official Visit to PRC </TI></H3>
<H4>   Proposes Island Development Zone </H4>
<F P=102> OW2701134894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1326 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2701134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Jan. 27 KYODO -- Russia has proposed a 
joint economic development zone with China on a disputed island 
on the Amur River that forms the border between the two 
countries, a high ranking Russian Foreign Ministry official said 
Thursday [27 January]. 
  The official told KYODO NEWS SERVICE that Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev presented the proposal to his Chinese 
counterpart Qian Qichen when the two met in Beijing the same 
day. 
  The official said Kozyrev suggested establishing the zone on 
Greater Ussuri Island, known in Chinese as Heixiazi Island. The 
Amur river is known as the Heilong river in Chinese. 
  If the Chinese side agrees to the proposal, it could serve 
as 
a "model" for resolving a border dispute between Japan and 
Russia over four islands to the north of Japan, the official 
said. 
  The disputed islands are Kunashiri, Etorofu, Shikotan and 
the 
Habomai islet group, all northeast of Hokkaido. They were 
seized from Japan by the former Soviet Union at the end of World 
War II. 
  In 1991, China and Russia signed an agreement settling some 
of their differences over their common border in the east, but 
several portions remain in dispute, including islands in the 
Amur River, where Chinese and Soviet soldiers fought battles in 
1969. 
  The official said Kozyrev and Jiang agreed that Chinese 
president Jiang Zemin will visit Moscow for the first time in 
either October or November this year. 
  The official said that prior to the visit, Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin will visit Beijing in May for talks 
with Chinese leaders, and Qian will then visit Moscow to 
finalize details of agreements to be signed during Jiang's visit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

