<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Discusses Deployment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2801015294 Moscow Radio Moscow in Korean 1200 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2801015294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Yuriy Solton from the "Today's World" program] </F>
  [Text] The United States plans to send Patriot missiles to 
South Korea. The Patriot missile was used in the Persian Gulf 
war and performed well. Station commentator Yuriy Solton writes 
on this: 
  The Pentagon discussed this matter at the request of the 
commander of the U.S. forces in South Korea, though President 
Clinton has not approved it yet. Quoting U.S. CIA materials, the 
Pentagon is planning to deploy Patriot missiles--which is an 
antimissile system--in South Korea because Pyonayang is capable 
of attacking U.S. military facilities with [word indistinct] 
missiles. 
  It is difficult to believe that such an attack is possible. 
First of all, recently the U.S. CIA said that a North Korean 
military aggression is almost impossible. Also, according to a 
report by an independent U.S. [word indistinct], the Nodong-1 
missile, which is modeled after a Scud-type missile, does not 
pose a big threat. 
  Considering these factors, it can be estimated that the plan 
to deploy Patriot missiles in South Korea is made to apply 
pressure on Pyongyang. It is also estimated that through such a 
pressure the United States attempts to lead North Korea to allow 
international inspections of its nuclear facilities which have 
been under the suspicion of developing nuclear weapons. 
  Pyongyang should have cleared such suspicion by returning to 
the Nonproliferation Treaty. However, the deployment of U.S. 
Patriot missiles in South Korea will not be conducive to solving 
the nuclear issue. Rather, it will lead Pyongyang to take 
countermeasures, thereby further aggravating the situation of 
the Korean penisula. 

</TEXT>

