<H3> <TI>   CIA's `Four Areas' of U.S. Interest in Russia Cited </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2701160094 Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA in Russian 27 Jan 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2701160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "Facts and Assessments" </F>
rubric: "What in Russia Interests CIA Director J. Woolsey?"] 
  [Text] He stated to Congress that there are "four vast 
areas" over there in which U.S. intelligence has been activated. 
First, it "provides our politicians with important, sometimes 
unique...analytical materials warning of the potential dangers 
being encountered" by Russia. Second, U.S. intelligence is 
"continuing to keep track of the location and condition of about 
27,000 Russian nuclear warheads." The third area of its work 
pertaining to Russia continues to be the "monitoring of the 
state of the Russian Federation general-purpose Armed Forces," 
James Woolsey said. The fourth major area is the "analysis of 
Russia'a policy vis-a-vis its neighbors." "It should be no 
surprise to anyone...that a crisis may arise in any political, 
social, and regional trouble spot in Russia and the remainder of 
the former USSR," he stated. 

</TEXT>

