<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Presses for UNSC Session on Bosnia in Geneva </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701185994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1726 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Even though the world community's response to the 
new Russian initiative concerning a settlement in Bosnia is 
"cautious, it makes it possible to go on with these efforts, 
above all with those aimed at convening the UN Security Council 
[UNSC] for a session in Geneva," said Russia's Deputy Foreign 
Minister, Vitaliy Churkin, on Thursday in answer to Interfax's 
question. 
  There is no intention of "forcing the European Union 
countries out of the process of settlement," he said at 
Thursday's briefing in Moscow. "We simply want to utilize the 
political weight and prestige of the UN Security Council to 
bring this affair (settlement: Interfax) to an end. It's not 
our fault that not all the European countries involved in this 
process are members of the UN Security Council," Russia's deputy 
foreign minister said. 
  Earlier on Thursday, Churkin said, he spoke with U.S. 
Ambassador Thomas Pickering about the new Russian initiative. 
According to him, the attitudes taken by the two countries have 
much in common. Nevertheless, he added, "neither Russia nor its 
European partners should look back at Washington all the time in 
their efforts to settle the crisis in Bosnia." 
  "As for the reaction of European countries, there is an 
impression that a session of the UN Security Council scares them 
more than the consequences of the war in Bosnia do," Churkin 
added. 

</TEXT>

