<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yazov: Gorbachev Gave No Written Orders on Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701174294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1508 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Belsky] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 27 TASS -- Former Soviet Defence 
Minister Dmitriy Yazov, one of the 1991 August failed coup 
leaders, now tried for high treason admitted on Thursday that 
troops had been brought into Moscow regularly between 1990 and 
1991 and it had never been registered in any documents. 
  Yazov said that in the majority of cases former Soviet 
President Mikhail Gorbachev had issued only "oral instructions," 
adding that even the deployment of troops in Baku in january 
1990 had not been preceded by such "formalities" as a written 
order of the Soviet president. 
  At the previous hearings, the former defence minister denied 
statements that plans had been made to storm the White House, 
the seat of Russian President Boris Yeltsin at that time. 
  He admitted that the coup attempt was unconstitutional as 
were the measures taken against the former soviet president who 
was removed from power and isolated at his Black Sea dacha. 
  He said the reasons for declaring a state of emergency in 
the 
former Soviet Union were extraordinary and much stronger than 
was envisaged by the law on the state of emergency. 
  Yazov stressed that he had ordered the troops on high alert, 
but denied he had ordered Soviet Air Forces on full combat 
readiness. He noted that all orders to the troops had been sent 
by the command of the airborne troops, who, apparently, have 
overstepped their powers. 

</TEXT>

