<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Navy Chief Kasatonov Visits Baltic Fleet Bases </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2701124394 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
2020 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM2701124394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By G. Sablin and A. Troshin from Kaliningrad; from the </F>
"Vesti" newscast] 
  [Text] [Sablin] The combat and tactical training of Baltic 
Fleet crews and ships deserves the highest appraisal. This 
opinion was expressed to journalists by Admiral Igor Kasatonov, 
first deputy commander in chief of the Navy, summing up the 
results of his visit to bases of Russia's oldest fleet. 
Dwelling on the timescale for the withdrawal naval forces from 
Latvia, he confirmed the readiness of the last major unit -- a 
submarine brigade -- to quit Liepaja by 1 June of this year. 
  At the same time Igor Kasatonov stressed that with the loss 
of its bases in Baltic countries, the Russian Navy will not lose 
its might or mobility. 
  [Admiral I. Kasatonov] Whereas the fleet now has 27 percent 
of nuclear warheads, this figure will rise to 42-47 percent by 
the year 2000. On 21 December I had the honor of being the 
senior Ministry of Defense official attending the laying of the 
keel of the latest submarine. In addition, the keels of a 
number of surface vessels have also been laid, and individual 
vessels have been commissioned. 
  However, the concept of a new fleet, the fleet for the third 
millenium, needs to be confirmed. Naturally, it will have to 
pass through government. 

</TEXT>

