<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Committee Chief on Future Arms Exports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK2701130094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 27 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK2701130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["ADS" report: "Russia Sells Fewer Weapons"] </F>
  [Text] Russian armaments and military hardware export last 
year was $2.117 billion (35 percent of 1990 exports); the export 
of civilian products was $513.6 million (26 percent of the 1990 
exports). This was reported on 26 January at the collegium of 
the State Committee on the Defense Industry by committee 
chairman Viktor Glukhikh. Export, according to him, should 
become one of the main sources of funds for the upkeep of the 
military production and research facilities because the 
purchases of armaments and military hardware, as well as budget 
appropriations for Russia's Defense Ministry, have been sharply 
curtailed. To be successful on the foreign market it is 
necessary to create a new system of organization of foreign 
economic activity by Defense Ministry enterprises. With this in 
mind, the State Committee on the Defense Industry has drawn up a 
draft law on Russia's military-technological cooperation with 
other countries, and a draft government decree granting to 
enterprises independence in foreign economic activities. Viktor 
Glukhikh thinks that the main role in the weapons market should 
belong to the developer and producer. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

