<DOCNO> FBIS3-57656 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov019_d_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-019 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sobchak: Problems Resolved During Yeltsin Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701202894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2014 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] St. Petersburg January 27 TASS -- "For the president 
when he is resolving the most important problems of the 
country's life, it is very important to see sentiments of the 
people, understand how they live, what they need and in what 
mood they are," mayor of St. Petersburg Anatoliy Sobchak told 
ITAR-TASS summing up the results of Boris Yeltsin's visit to St. 
Petersburg where he participated in the festivities devoted to 
the fiftieth anniversary of the full lifting of the blockade of 
Leningrad during World War II. 
  Despite this holiday, the head of state and the leadership 
of 
the city and the region, at a meeting behind closed doors, 
managed to discuss a wide range of actual problems for the 
region which demanded the settlement at the presidential level. 
  According to Anatoliy Sobchak, the president promised to 
support the St. Petersburg authorities in financing, from the 
federal budget, the construction of new metro lines which are 
extremely necessary to the city. The mayor of St. Petersburg 
obtained Boris Yeltsin's consent to promote the St. Petersburg 
project of accomplishing the construction of the dam [as 
received]. This issue will be submitted for the Russian 
Government's consideration. 
  Participants in the meeting discussed the possibilities of 
crediting of house building which is very actual for St. 
Petersburg where considerable part of the population are still 
living in shared flats. The spectrum of issues discussed today 
was extremely wide, also including subsidizing products of stock 
breeding which are delivered to St. Petersburg from the 
Leningrad region, timely receipt of funds for the preparation 
for the Good Will Games due to be held in summer, and quoting 
some kinds of goods. 
  Special attention was paid to the settlement of problems 
with 
petrol taking into account that the Surgut Company is the 
monopolist in petrol deliveries to St. Petersburg and therefore 
maintains prices for this fuel at the highest level in the 
country. According to Anatoliy Sobchak, the city authorities 
proposed to the president the mechanism for overcoming the 
monopolism in this field, and the president intends to sign an 
appropriate decree. 
  The sensation of the day was the St. Petersburg mayor's 
report that Boris Yeltsin agreed in principle to turn the city 
of Kronshtadt into a free economic zone. This city will be 
stage-by- stage opened up for tourists and citizens of St. 
Petersburg. The navy base located on the territory of 
Kronshtadt will have to be moved to some other place. According 
to Anatoliy Sobchak, Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev who 
was present at the meeting said "yes" on this issue. 
  In addition, many problems concerning the Leningrad region 
were solved at the Russian president's meeting with the 
leadership of this region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

