<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Doubts Treaty Will Guarantee Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701215194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 2036 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701215194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chairman of the Ukrainian parliament's Commission on 
Legislation and Law, a leader of the Ukrainian Communist Party, 
Aleksandr Kotsuba, doubted that the ratification of the Moscow 
statement of the three presidents (U.S.A., Russia and Ukraine -- 
IF) could "guarantee the total security of Ukraine." 
  He said in an interview with INTERFAX-Ukraine that it was 
necessary to consider some provisions of the trilateral 
statement in the parliament. In his words, it was hard to 
understand "why primarily the SS-24 missiles controlled by us 
must be withdrawn from Ukrainian territory and not the obsolete 
SS-19 which we do not control and cannot launch." 
  In his opinion, "it was necessary to demand the 
states-parties to the Helsinki, Paris, Vienna and Lisbon 
agreements and the UN member-states to participate in the 
agreement of the three presidents. It is necessary that not 
only Ukraine give up its missiles but that the other parties 
also reduce their numbers," Kotsuba pointed out. 
  He said that the president and the cabinet of ministers 
through the Ukrainian Foreign Ministry should initiate a number 
of treaties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

