<H3> <TI>   No Extra Arms From Russia Shipped </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2701160294 Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1300 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2701160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1300 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Armenian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quoting official sources at the Azerbaijani Defense 
Ministry, TURAN reported that the dispatch of military hardware 
and arms from Russia to Armenia has been stepped up in recent 
days. According to Azerbaijani intelligence data, the arms and 
military hardware are being flown from Sochi to Gyumri on board 
military cargo planes. The same source says the Russian 
military cargo planes are carrying out around 30 flights a day. 
  TURAN claims that Armenia has already received a few dozen 
modern tanks from Russia. According to the news agency, the 
arms dispatch was stepped up following Armenian defeats on the 
battlefront. 
  As proof, TURAN cites an AFP correspondent in Armenia 
claiming that officials in Yerevan are not hiding that the flow 
of military hardware from Russia became possible after Yegor 
Gaydar resigned; he was stingy about this. 
  In connection with untrue Azerbaijani press reports, a SNARK 
reporter asked Seyran (Shakhbugaryan), the head of the Armenian 
Defense Ministry Press Service, to comment on this issue. 
(Shakhbugaryan) stated that the military cooperation between 
Russia and Armenia is in line with the status of the Russian 
troops in Armenia. Beyond that, no arms have ever or are being 
dispatched. 

</TEXT>

