<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Outlines Armed Forces' Current Strength </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2701161594 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 27 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2701161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Valeriy Gromak: "Relying on NATO.... Will Draft </F>
New Regulations Help Real Strengthening of Latvian Armed 
Forces?"] 
  [Text] Riga -- The Latvian Defense Ministry has prepared 
new regulations for drafting people into active military 
service. They envisage reducing the categories of citizens who 
are exempt from compulsory military service. 
  Currently there are 6,500 people serving in the Latvian 
Armed 
Forces, 550 of them officers. These figures break down as 
follows: There are 1,500 enlisted men and 150 officers serving 
in the Army, 3,800 enlisted men and 340 officers in the Border 
Guard, 600 seamen and 30 officers in the Navy, and 150 enlisted 
men and 30 officers in the Air Force. 
  The Latvian Navy has 15 ships and combat craft, of which six 
are undergoing repair and two are mothballed. The Air Force has 
two An-2 aircraft, two L-410 transporters, and six Mi-2 
helicopters. One aircraft and four helicopters are combat ready. 
  Latvia wants to guarantee its national security primarily by 
joining NATO. As we know, to date these efforts have not been 
successful. And some news agencies report that the Latvian 
Government has decided to allocate funds to buy two Russian Mi-8 
helicopters.... 

</TEXT>

