<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev Issues Appeal for Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801113494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1109 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2801113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Maynayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek January 28 TASS -- Kyrgyz President Askar 
Akayev issued today an appeal to the Kyrgyz people entitled "I 
am guiltless before people and before my own conscience." He 
took this step in connection with a referendum, scheduled for 
January 30, which should give an answer to the question: Can the 
president continue to discharge his duties or not? The reason 
for the referendum is that the Kyrgyz Constitution, adopted on 
May 5, made illegitimate all branches of power existing in the 
republic, which was used as a pretext by the forces opposing 
Akayev. As a politician, the president decided to resolve the 
problem with the help of a nationwide referendum. 
  Akayev explained the essence of his policy in the appeal. He 
maintains that "now the majority of people in our republic and 
all political forces favour a market-based economy, economic 
freedom for the strong and social protection for the week." 
Despite a rather difficult economic situation in the republic 
and the continuing decline of living standards, the president 
believes that "solid economic preconditions have been created 
for the people to feel the first accomplishments, brought by our 
economic reform, in 1994, for us to start living just a little 
better." 
  "If the Kyrgyz people support me at the popular referendum, 
I 
shall stick to the policy of reform, the policy which will 
ensure, in the long run, the well-being of our people and the 
prosperity of the republic," Akayev stressed in the appeal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

