<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Concerned Over Churkin Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801155694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1414 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2801155694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Estonia's Foreign Ministry has expressed concern 
over statements made by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy 
Churkin at a news conference on Thursday. 
  In a press release issued on Friday, the Estonian ministry 
welcomed Churkin's "condemnation" of the 1940 events but 
denounced his refusal to qualify them as the annexation or 
occupation of the Baltic states by the Soviet Union or as a 
Soviet aggression against them. 
  "International law did not begin in 1945, as Mr. Churkin 
asserts," the ministry says. 
  It says Estonia has for a long time "shown patience and 
goodwill and has made many concessions in order to solve 
problems which it inherited from the 50 years of Soviet 
occupation." 
  The ministry says the fact that Russian officials have 
completely ignored Estonia's efforts and have instead made a 
series of propaganda attacks and poorly concealed threats does 
not serve to strengthen trust or ensure stability. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

