<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Progress Reported in Preparations for Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2701170694 Tallinn BNS in English 1336 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2701170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 27, BNS -- Next to no progress has 
been achieved in recent months in preparing the Estonian-Russian 
summit, Foreign Ministry Chancellor Alar Olljum told BNS. 
  Russia made an official proposal for a meeting between 
President Boris Yeltsin and President Lennart Meri last autumn. 
The summit was then expected to take place in November or 
December. 
  Olljum reiterated that the meeting between the presidents 
can 
take place only after the principal issues of the 
Estonian-Russian relations have been resolved. He had in mind 
in the first place the setting of the final deadline for the 
Russian troop withdrawal. 
  "From the first, we were not sure the summit could soon take 
place," Olljum told BNS. "It was primarily Russia's statement 
that sparked interest in the press." 
  Olljum voiced hope that the troop withdrawal deadline -- 
Aug. 
31 -- proposed by Russia will be officially confirmed at the 
upcoming meeting between the Russian and the Estonian 
delegations next week. 
  Estonia agreed to the deadline in principle but will not 
accept any strings. 
  When Russia for the first time suggested the August deadline 
last autumn, it made a number of stipulations concerning "social 
protection" of Russians residing in Estonia, money for housing 
construction, and other issues. 
  Olljum expressed the opinion this was a "propagandistic 
step." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

