<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Fuel Shortage Reduces Personnel Training </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2801115094 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1800 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM2801115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Vladimir Plotnikov; from the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The generals have developed various options for 
Ukraine's territorial defense without leaving their 
headquarters. Guns, tanks, and other combat equipment has also 
remained at the dpots, first because no orders have been given 
and, second, because there are no fuels or lubricants. It was 
for this reason that the movement of combat vehicles has been 
stopped or reduced to the absolute minimum. To study 
instruments on tanks, for example, they are not started up but 
simply given an electric charge. In other words, the Ukrainian 
army has found itself in the grips of an energy crisis, just 
like the whole of the country's national economic complex. 
Firing from an ordinary rifle is virtually the only accessible 
element of fire training. 
  Yet over the same period rumors have spread in Ukraine that 
large-scale military exercises are being conducted in Crimea. 
  [Crimean Supreme Council Chairman N. Bagrov] Any exercises 
on 
Crimean territory are coordinated with the Supreme Council and 
the Presidium. I repeat that the reports you mention are 
disinformation. No exercises are being conducted on Crimea's 
territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

