<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Progress M-21' Spacecraft Launched 28 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801071694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0656 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2801071694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow January 28 TASS -- The automatically 
controlled cargo spacecraft Progress M-21 was launched today at 
05.12, Moscow time. 
  The purpose of its launching is to deliver various cargoes 
to 
the Mir orbital complex. 
  The Progress M-21 was put into orbit with the following 
parametres: 
  -- maximum distance from the earth's surface -- 236 km, 
  -- minimum distance from the earth's surface -- 194 km, 
  -- period of revolution -- 88.5 minutes, 
  -- inclination -- 51.6 degrees. 
  According to the telemetric information, the on-board 
systems 
of the cargo spacecraft are functioning normally. 
  The total weight of the cargo, together with fuel, is about 
two tonnes. Viktor Afanasiev, Yuriy Usachev and Valeriy 
Polyakov, who are working at the Mir orbital station, will 
receive the equipment they need, fuel, materials for scientific 
research, food, as well as parcels from their families. Aside 
from it, manual TV-controlled regime equipment will be tested at 
the Progress M-21. 
  The crew of the 15th main expedition will receive a total of 
three cargo spacecraft. 

</TEXT>

