<H3> <TI>   Russia's Choice Warns Power Shifting to Premier </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701174194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1408 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701174194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The new cabinet's make up may well support 
speculation that the Chernomyrdin government will try to roll 
back the reforms, secretary of the Russia's Choice Party in 
parliament Sergey Yushenkov told reporters on Thursday. 
  In his words, Chernomyrdin has managed to persuade the 
President and form a cabinet of his own choice, an indication of 
a gradual shift of federal authority to the Prime Minister. 
  For his part, RC public relations officer Kirill Ignatiyev 
said the party would ensure political support to its five 
ministers in the cabinet carrying out RC goals. 
  These are Vice Premier Anatoliy Chubays, Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev, Science and Education Minister Boris Saltykov, 
Minister of Culture Yevgeniy Sidorov and Environment Minister 
Viktor Danilov-Danilyan. 
  Saltykov in turn has said he will remain in the cabinet as 
long as he can implement reforms within his area of 
responsibility. 
  Yushenkov hopes the Russian President is well aware of how 
fatal it will be to wind up reforms and will be able to muster 
up enough strength to take appropriate decisions. 
  He said that under the constitution, Yeltsin can name a 
Prime 
Minister but not individual ministers. 
  The RC is ready to bring a non-confidence motion against the 
government if it adopts unacceptable resolutions including one 
on the budget, Yushenkov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

