<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lobov Tipped To Head Presidential Body </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK2801100094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 28 Jan 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK2801100094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Maksim Isayev report under the "Perspective" rubric: </F>
"President Has Not Forgotten About `Power' Ministries and 
December Elections. Serious Reshuffles in Defense Ministry May 
Follow Two or Three Months From Now"] 
  [Text] According to confidential information received from 
presidential structures, the question about the first deputy 
prime minister in charge of the "power" ministries has been put 
on ice for the next two or three months. At the same time, 
there still remains the question about what practical 
conclusions should be drawn in the Ministry of Internal Affairs, 
Defense Ministry, Foreign Intelligence Service, and the Federal 
Counterintelligence Service on the results of the December 
voting, and who and in what way is going to guarantee the 
loyalty of these structures to the present authority in the 
future. Work is proceeding apace in this connection on the 
creation of a special presidential organ for "oversight" of the 
"power" ministries, an organ that would inspect all types of 
their activities as well as take care of "ideological" work and 
personnel policy. 
  The most probable candidates to take over the position of 
head of this organ are Yevgeniy Shaposhnikov and Oleg Lobov. 
Incidentally, it has transpired that Mr. Lobov has become the 
head of a special commission that has begun compiling efficiency 
rating reports on Federal Counterintelligence Service staffers. 
This and Lobov's special relationship with the president 
increase his chances, while he is also sure going to keep his 
post of Security Council secretary. In this situation, Yevgeniy 
Shaposhnikov would quit the army to become Russia's first 
civilian defense minister. 
  The president is not likely to push Pavel Grachev completely 
aside, although many things will come into focus following the 
investigation in the State Duma defense committee into unseemly 
facts some experts think have a direct bearing on the current 
defense minister. 

</TEXT>

