<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Will Not Allow `Backtrack From Reforms' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701165094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1633 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] St. Petersburg January 27 TASS -- Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin is upset with his failure to persuade Boris 
Fedorov and Ella Pamfilova to stay in the government, 
presidential spokesman Vyacheslav Kostikov said. 
  In an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS on Thursday, 
Kostikov warned against attempts to overdramatise the situation. 
  Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin has repeatedly said 
lately 
that he will remain adherent to the course of reform, Kostikov 
said. At the same time, he said Chernomyrdin's statements at the 
recent agricultural conference in Oryol, Central Russia, 
resembled "the distribution of unbaked bread" and caused certain 
alarm. "The president is closely watching the situation in the 
government and will not allow (anyone) to backtrack from reforms 
while publicly pledging (one's) adherence to them," the 
spokesman said. 
  He recalled that the new government has been working only a 
few days since the reshuffle and has not taken any real steps 
yet. "The president is inclined to judge by deeds, not by 
words," Kostikov added. He noted that the president is 
concerned about statements which can be interpreted as partial 
restoration of "the administrative-command distribution and 
state planning system." 
  "Under the new Constitution, the president has enough powers 
and possibilities to direct the government and insist on the 
continuation of the course chosen by Russia, the spokesman said. 
  Asked about Yeltsin's relations with the parliament, 
Kostikov 
replied that the tragic experience of the October events in 
Moscow has given food for thought for both the president and the 
parliament. The president was the first to draw conclusions and 
meet with the heads of the parliament houses. "I think the 
deputy corps which has passed the trial of democratic elections 
is interested in constructive interaction with the president," 
Kostikov continued. He said number one task is to isolate 
extremist forces in the parliament. 
  Kostikov said that the president is preparing a message to 
the parliament in which he will outline the main tasks facing 
the country. It will reiterate his adherence to the 
continuation of the tough anti-inflationary policy and 
privatisation as one of the key prerequisites for the country's 
transfer to a market economy. These measures will be 
accompanied by social welfare guarantees, especially for those 
in need. "No one will give out unbaked bread from uncollected 
wheat," the spokesman said. 
  "The president has no intention of interfering in the 
operative work of the government and wants to see what the 
corrections proposed by Viktor Chernomyrdin will give. There 
may be various variants of tactics, but the president has a 
clear-cut limit, that is the continuation of reform. If he sees 
that a tendency towards its curtailment has emerged, he will nip 
that tendency in the bud," Kostikov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57732 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov019_b_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-019 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soskovets: Main Task To `Bring Order' to Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2701162094 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 27 Jan 94 
First Edition p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PM2701162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aleksandr Golyayev: "Oleg Soskovets: We Must </F>
Bring Order to the Economy"] 
  [Text] The latest conference of the government commission 
on operational questions went on for over three hours and 
examined measures to stabilize the work of the aluminum industry. 
  As in other sectors of the national economy, problems have 
been building up here and they are holding back production 
development. The situation is aggravated by the fact that prices 
of this metal have slumped on the world market (we are largely 
responsible for this) and demand has fallen in Russia itself. 
The enterprise leaders addressing the conference insisted that 
some kind of influence be brought to bear on the energy 
industry, which has raised the prices of its products -- in 
their view, this is inhibiting the sector's development. But, 
as Railways Minister Gennadiy Fadeyev, who also came in for a 
great deal of criticism, said at the conference, you cannot 
generate your own economic prosperity at the expense of others. 
  After the conference First Vice Premier Oleg Soskovets 
answered journalists' questions: 
  [Question] How is the government reorganization going to 
continue, indeed there is still one first deputy chairman 
vacancy? 
  [Soskovets] There isn't a second first vice premier's post 
in the plan that I possess. Nor is there an industry 
commission, which I allegedly head. 
  [Question] The resignations of Gaydar and Fedorov got people 
saying that the reforms were over. What do you think? 
  [Soskovets] I do not see in what way Fedorov and Gaydar are 
more market-orientated than I.... The government's main task? 
We must bring order to Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

