<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Urges Referendum on Fate of Skrunda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2701211794 Tallinn BNS in English 1844 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2701211794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 27, BNS -- Latvia should stage a 
referendum to decide on the fate of the Russian-operated radar 
station in Skrunda, the Baltic nation's President Guntis Ulmanis 
told local authorities in the Ludza town. 
  MPs cannot not assume the enormous responsibility for the 
future and the health of people in Latvia if the problem is as 
important as the Skrunda issue is, Ulmanis said Jan. 26. 
  Latvia has evidence of new-type radiation across its 
territory what could be aimed at determining movements of space 
objects, Ulmanis said. In his opinion, Russia is looking for 
new ways to control the airspace above Europe and Latvia. 
  If the guesses prove right, Latvia could possibly attain 
reduction of the term for the preservation of the radar station, 
the president said. 
  As reported, Russia wants to keep the radar for five more 
years. If Latvia agrees to this condition, Russia will complete 
the withdrawal of its troops by September, said Russian 
delegation head Sergei Zotov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

