<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Wants To Meet Kebich; Views Change </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2701211194 Tallinn BNS in English 1609 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2701211194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 27, BNS -- Lithuanian Prime Minister 
Adolfas Slezevicius said he needs to meet with his Belarusian 
counterpart Vyacheslav Kebich. 
  Kebich survived a no confidence vote in the Belarussian 
parliament Wednesday [26 January], but the Belarusian lawmakers 
managed to oust Parliament Chairman Stanislav Shushkevich. 
  Commenting on the developments in Minsk, Slezevicius told 
reporters Thursday that the search for solutions to several 
disputed problems, like the Adutiskis railroad station, has 
stopped and experts have "used up their ability" to deal with 
these matters. 
  The Lithuanian premier said he is glad that Lithuania joins 
NATO's Partnership for Peace program. "We want Lithuania to be 
among the first in this field, and this is a very important step 
in enhancing security and considering Kozyrev's (Russian foreign 
minister) statements." 
  Commenting on the Lithuanian Social Democratic Party's 
proposal to take a no confidence vote in the government, 
Slezevicius said the initiative is a "normal action...and the 
right of all politicians and political parties." 
  The premier said the social democrats simply try "to attract 
attention to a petty party that is poorly represented in the 
parliament." 
  Slezevicius said the earlier governments failed to stabilize 
the economy and to stop crime. 

</TEXT>

