<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidium Nominates Candidates for Post of Speaker </TI></H3>
<H4>   TASS Reports Three Candidates </H4>
<F P=102> LD2801101694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0929 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2801101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By BELINFORM for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Minsk January 28 TASS -- Three lawmakers remained in 
the list of candidates for the post of the Belarusian speaker 
after consultations among lawmakers, self-nominations and 
refusal of some candidates to join the race. 
  First Deputy Speaker Vyacheslav Kuznetsov told the 
parliament 
on Friday [28 January] that the three are Mechislaw Hryb, 
chairman of the parliamentary commission on national security, 
defence and anti-crime fight, Mikhail Marynych, deputy chairman 
of the state committee on foreign economic relations, and 
lawmaker Viktar Hanchar. Prime Minister Vyacheslav Kebich 
refused to vie the post. 
  Hryb and Marynych were nominated by the presidium of the 
parliament which held a meeting on Thursday and which was 
attended by Kebich and heads of republic's regions. 
  The presidium also nominated three other candidates -- 
Nikolay Voytenkov, head of the Gomel region, Viktor Danilenko, 
the ambassador in Russia, and Vladimir Rusakevich, deputy head 
of the Brest region. However, the three immediately announced 
that they quit the race. 
  Hanchar was nominated by Aleksandr Lukashenko who initiated 
the no-confidence vote to former speaker Stanislav Shushkevich. 
  Other candidates nominated by lawmakers included Prime 
Minister Vyacheslav Kebich, Chairman of the Party of Popular 
Accord Gennadiy Karpenko and Ambassador in Latvia Valentin 
Velichko. However, they all withdrew themselves from the list. 

</TEXT>

