<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   International Economic Forum Held in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Addresses Plenary Session </H4>
<F P=102> LD3001212294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2059 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3001212294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Nikita Yermakov and Konstantin </F>
Pribytkov] 
  [Text] Davos, Switzerland, January 30 TASS--Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin's policy of an in-depth democratic 
reform of Russian society, the economy and political 
institutions will be continued with due regard, primarily, for 
the national and strategic interests of Russia and proceeding 
from the principles inherent in the new Russian Constitution, 
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin told a plenary 
meeting of the World Economic Forum here on Sunday night. 
  Touching upon the problem of foreign investments in the 
Russian economy, Chernomyrdin emphasised that last year had seen 
no cardinal changes as regards Russia's readiness for 
cooperation. Inside Russia, conditions for the operation of 
foreign investors gradually change, albeit too slowly, he said. 
  Russia can accept and "digest" foreign investments amounting 
to at least 10,000-12,000 million U.S. dollars a year, not as 
"aid" but on mutually beneficial commercial terms, Chernomyrdin 
said. 
  "We are prepared for joint work in this respect, to set up, 
in particular, a multilateral council of foreign and Russian 
bankers, investors, and entrepreneurs and jointly examine 
investment cooperation possibilities with respect to particular 
sectors and enterprises," the Russian prime minister said. 
  Chernomyrdin expressed readiness to participate in the work 
of such a council, a session which could be held in Moscow in 
May-June. 
  In conclusion, the Russian premier voiced hope that the 
World 
Economic Forum would promote the understanding of the processes 
taking place in Russia. 
  Then he answered questions asked by plenary meeting 
participants. 
  January saw a campaign during which Russia was accused of 
curtailing reforms and the Russian Government was alleged to 
have a desire to reverse the reform process. 
  "I would like to state once again: Russia will not turn 
backwards and will not swerve off the road of reforms. This is 
guaranteed, primarily, by the Constitution which reflects the 
realities of a democratic society, democratic Russia. We have 
the president who is the guarantor of what we do now. You may 
rest assured that my government will go ahead with reforms and 
will not turn off the road," Chernomyrdin said. 

</TEXT>

