<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   International Economic Forum Held in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets Western Leaders in Davos </H4>
<F P=102> LD3101091694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0705 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Nikita Yermakov and Konstantin </F>
Pribytkov] 
  [Text] Davos January 31 TASS -- Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin held a series of meetings with 
representatives of political and business circles of Western 
countries during his two-day visit to the Swiss resort city of 
Davos to attend the World Economic Forum. 
  Chernomyrdin met with Swedish Prime Minister Carl Bildt, 
Swiss federal adviser Jean-Pascal Delamuraz, OPEC Secretary 
General Subroto, EBRD [European Bank for Reconstruction and 
Development] directors and managers of a number of major 
commercials banks. 
  "We have attained our goal at the talks -- there was a 
thorough and professional discussion of problems and 
difficulties faced by Russia," Valentin Sergeyev, head of the 
press service of the Russian Government, told ITAR-TASS. "There 
is no question of reforms or no reforms on today's agenda. We 
are for reforms, but the question is how they should be carried 
out, who should help us and by what means the reforms should be 
fulfilled," Sergeyev said. 
  "The forum in Davos was beneficial for all, including the 
West and Russia, for the general comprehension of problems we 
are facing today and which might arise tomorrow," Sergeyev said. 
He pointed out that in the opinion of the Russian delegation, 
this time the talks were not merely a discussion in character, 
which shows that a new stage in the comprehension of Russia's 
problems has begun. "It was not the question of what to do but 
rather how this should be done that was at issue," Sergeyev said. 
  "Our cooperation with the West is not merely a declaration, 
but quite a concrete matter. Earlier, we discussed aid, whereas 
today, we are speaking about mutually advantageous cooperation, 
while the word "aid" sounds like nonsense. Today, we are not 
merely discussing investments, but rather ways in which Russian 
goods, but not only raw materials, can enter the world market. 
In short, the Davos forum has risen to a qualitatively new 
level in its businesslike atmosphere, approaches and expected 
results," Sergeyev said. 

</TEXT>

