<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   International Economic Forum Held in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Uzbek President Comments </H4>
<F P=102> LD3001065494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0640 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3001065494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Nikita Yermakov and Konstantin </F>
Pribytkov] 
  [Text] Davos January 30 TASS -- Uzbek President Islam 
Karimov, currently attending a world economic forum in 
Switzerland, said in an interview with ITAR-TASS that countries 
of the former Soviet Union are stronger now than a year ago and 
seek economic cooperation which might pave the way for resolving 
political issues. 
  "The euphoria which all of us experienced in a purely 
political aspect when everyone advocated sovereignty, is 
weakening," Karimov said, he pointed out that "political 
sovereignty appeared to rest on economic issues", adding that 
economic independence turned out to be more important than the 
political one and that there was a growing desire to communicate 
with each other in a purely economic aspect. 
  Karimov drew particular attention to the situation in 
Ukraine, pointing out that there were times when this republic 
occupied a kind of an isolated position. "I think that was a 
mistake," Karimov said. "Today, we strongly need economic 
cooperation which will promote the solution of political 
problems," the Uzbek president said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

