<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Uzbek, Kyrgyz, Kazakh Defense Ministers Meet in Bishkek </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801200694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1414 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2801200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Defense Ministers of Kyrgyzstan, Uzbekistan, and 
Kazakhstan held a working meeting in Bishkek on Friday [28 
January]. 
  As the Kazakh minister Sagan Nurmukhametov told newsmen 
after 
the session, the sides signed a protocol on mutual assistance 
and on republican resources for their armies' logistic supplies. 
  He stressed that the meeting least of all meant secession 
from the CIS Collective Security Treaty. On the contrary, he 
said, its results will contribute to broader cooperation between 
the collective security pact members. 
  As Uzbek Defense Minister Rustam Akhmedov remarked, the 
consultations pave the way for closer ties between the three 
Central Asian states in anti-aircraft defense and in other 
fields. He voiced hope that Russia would join the alliance, 
since it was interested in reinforcing its southern borders more 
than any other state. 
  The Uzbek and Kyrgyz ministers also signed a bilateral 
cooperation accord for 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

