<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgian Minister on Serbs' `Crushing Responsibility' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012164393 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3012164393 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] Foreign Minister Willy Claes is 
very disappointed by the lack of progress on the situation in 
former Yugoslavia. Annie Lameus reports: 
  [Lameus] Willy Claes deplored the fact that the warring 
parties were driven by a logic of war rather than peace, and he 
reserved particularly harsh criticism for the leader of the 
Bosnian Serbs, Radovan Karadzic: 
  [Begin Claes recording] The Serbian side continues to bear a 
crushing responsibility in this tragedy. I cannot find a single 
good thing to say about someone like Karadzic, whom I consider 
one of those most to blame for this tragedy. Even in general, 
however, when, like school teachers, we ask these various 
gentlemen whether they are prepared to commit themselves to a 
cease-fire over a given period -- with international public 
opinion as their witnesses -- and these gentlemen answer yes 
without the slightest hesitation and then we see that nothing, 
but nothing, is respected, then we have to ask ourselves some 
questions. [end recording] 
  On 1 January, Greece will take over the European Presidency. 
Greece still refuses to recognize the Former Yugoslav Republic 
of Macedonia as long as it bears the name Macedonia. Other 
European countries have recognized this republic and, this 
morning, Willy Claes announced that Belgium would soon be doing 
the same. 

</TEXT>

