<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   30,000 Russian Soldiers Remain in Germany </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0101104794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0714 GMT 1 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0101104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- At the end of 1993, three 
years after the Russian Western Group (WGT) began to withdraw 
troops from Germany, there were only 30,000 soldiers of the 
former Eastern victorious power left in eastern Germany. That 
is less than 10 percent of the 337,800 troops stationed here at 
the beginning of 1991. 
  Major General Hartmut Foertsch, the Federal Government 
official in charge of the withdrawal and head of the German 
liaison command for the WGT, told DDP/ADN in an interview that 
the former First Strategic Echelon of the Soviet Army and the 
Warsaw Pact was withdrawing from Germany "according to plan." 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

