<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Monarchist Party Announces Formation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0201211494 Paris AFP in English 2038 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0201211494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bari, Italy, Jan 2 (AFP) -- A new political party, 
the Italian Democratic Monarchist Party (PDIM), announced its 
formation Sunday [2 January], pledging to return Italy to a 
monarchy nearly half a century after it became a republic. 
  The party's national executive said in a statement issued in 
this southern city that it would take part in legislative 
elections due this year, and would work towards the election of 
a monarchist president by the people. 
  The party however refused to pledge allegiance to Victor 
Emmanuel of Savoy, the direct descendent of Italy's last king, 
Umberto II, saying they only recognized the former's cousin 
Amedee, Duke of Aoste. The party's leaders described themselves 
as Savoy's loyalists. 
  Italy became a republic on June 10, 1946 after a referendum. 
The vote ended the reign of the House of Savoy, whose kings had 
ruled over Piedmont for nine centuries and as kings of Italy 
from 1861. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57797 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu001_o_94001" </HT>


